      {
        "id": 2771982,
        "name": null,
        "username": "JFPelletier",
        "avatar_template": "/user_avatar/www.wineberserkers.com/jfpelletier/{size}/2283_2.png",
        "created_at": "2019-12-14T00:41:04.000Z",
        "cooked": "<aside class=\"quote no-group\" data-post=\"3\" data-topic=\"156803\">\n<blockquote>\n<p>The Clos de la Baronne is owned by American investors, IIRC, and it produces a fatter, fleshier wine. The Clos de la Barre is one of the emblematic wines from the domaine from a superior terroir, and if I\u2019m not mistaken was the original lieu-dit bottled Meursault that started it all. It produces a wine with more tension and aging potential.</p>\n</blockquote>\n</aside>\n<p>Thanks. That\u2019s what I thought. I was sorely disappointed to not get the 2014 Clos de la Barre\u2026</p>\n<p>Cheers!</p>\n<p>JF</p>",
